  "Old Lighting": {
    page1: "Before electric light bulbs, people relied on fire-based light sources like candles, oil lamps, and gas lamps to see after dark. These older forms of lighting were dimmer, more expensive to maintain, and posed a greater fire risk than modern electric lighting. Families often had limited hours of usable light each day, which shaped daily routines like when people worked, cooked, and slept. Understanding old lighting methods helps explain why the invention of the electric light bulb was such a major change in daily life.",
    page2: "For most of human history, the only light after sunset came from fire, whether from open flames, candles, or oil-burning lamps. Candles, typically made from animal fat, called tallow, or beeswax, were common in homes for centuries but produced weak, flickering light and could be costly. In the 1800s, gas lighting became common in cities, piping flammable gas to street lamps and indoor fixtures that had to be lit by hand. These methods all required constant attention, refueling, or lighting, and none produced light as bright or safe as later electric bulbs.",
    page3: "Candles were widely used from ancient times through the 1800s and required frequent replacing since they burned down and produced soot. Oil lamps, often burning whale oil or kerosene, became popular in the 1700s and 1800s and provided somewhat brighter, steadier light than candles. Gas lighting, introduced to city streets and homes in the early 1800s, allowed for brighter and more consistent lighting but carried risks of leaks and explosions. Thomas Edison's practical incandescent light bulb, developed in 1879, eventually replaced these older methods because it was safer, brighter, and more convenient.",
    page4: "Using old lighting methods required regular effort, such as trimming candle wicks, refilling lamp oil, or lighting gas fixtures each evening. Households had to budget carefully for fuel, since candles, oil, and gas all cost money and needed to be resupplied. Cities that adopted gas street lighting needed workers, called lamplighters, whose job was to light and extinguish street lamps every day. The switch to electric lighting eliminated most of this daily labor once power lines and bulbs became widely available in the late 1800s and early 1900s.",
    page5: "Inventors and scientists across the 1800s worked to improve lighting, competing to create a light source that was brighter, safer, and cheaper to run. Thomas Edison is often credited with the practical light bulb, though he built on the work of earlier inventors and focused on creating a long-lasting, affordable design along with the electrical systems needed to power it. Families who could not afford newer lighting technology continued using candles and oil lamps well after electric lighting became available in cities. The shift to electric light changed how people spent their evenings, extending the hours available for reading, working, and socializing.",
    page6: "The move from fire-based lighting to electric bulbs reduced fire hazards in homes and cities and made nighttime activity far more common and practical. Electric lighting supported longer working hours in factories and offices, contributing to economic and social changes in the late 1800s and early 1900s. It also improved safety in public spaces, as electric street lighting was more reliable than gas lamps. Old lighting methods are still occasionally used today, such as candles during power outages or for decoration.",
    page7: "Before electric bulbs, people lit their homes with candles, oil lamps, and gas lighting, all of which were dimmer, costlier, and more dangerous than electric light. These methods required daily upkeep, like lighting wicks or refilling fuel, and shaped how much could be done after dark. Thomas Edison's 1879 light bulb eventually replaced these older sources with something safer and more convenient. The shift to electric lighting changed daily routines and helped enable longer working and waking hours."
  }
