  "Thomas Jefferson": {
    page1: "Thomas Jefferson was the third president of the United States, serving from 1801 to 1809, and is best known as the primary author of the Declaration of Independence. Born in Virginia in 1743, he was a lawyer, planter, architect, and inventor with wide-ranging interests in science, philosophy, and government. He helped shape the ideas at the core of American democracy, particularly the belief that people have unalienable rights to life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness. His influence stretched from the founding of the country through his presidency and beyond.",
    page2: "By the 1770s, the American colonies were increasingly frustrated with British taxation and rule without representation in Parliament. Jefferson, already known for his skilled writing, was chosen by the Second Continental Congress in 1776 to draft the Declaration of Independence, explaining the colonies' reasons for separating from Britain. After independence was won, Jefferson served in several important roles, including governor of Virginia, minister to France, and the first Secretary of State under President Washington. His political rivalry with Alexander Hamilton over the power of the federal government helped create the earliest American political parties.",
    page3: "Jefferson wrote most of the Declaration of Independence in 1776, including its famous statement that \"all men are created equal\" and are entitled to \"unalienable Rights.\" As president, his most significant achievement was the Louisiana Purchase in 1803, which bought roughly 828,000 square miles of land from France and doubled the size of the United States. He then commissioned the Lewis and Clark Expedition to explore this new western territory. He also founded the University of Virginia and designed his own home, Monticello, reflecting his interest in architecture and education.",
    page4: "As president, Jefferson worked to reduce the size and cost of the federal government, cutting military spending and taxes while still managing to fund the Louisiana Purchase. He negotiated the Louisiana Purchase through diplomats in France, taking advantage of France's need for money during European wars. He sent Meriwether Lewis and William Clark on a two-year expedition, from 1804 to 1806, to map the new territory, find a route to the Pacific, and establish relations with Native American nations. His presidency balanced practical governing decisions with his deeper philosophical commitment to limited government and individual liberty.",
    page5: "Jefferson was a brilliant and complex figure, deeply devoted to ideals of liberty and equality while also enslaving over 600 people during his lifetime at Monticello. Historians continue to study the contradiction between his writings on human equality and his own practice of slavery, including his long relationship with an enslaved woman named Sally Hemings, with whom he had children. He was also known for his intellectual curiosity, corresponding with scientists, inventing devices, and amassing one of the largest personal libraries in America, which later became the foundation of the Library of Congress. Many historians view him as a brilliant but deeply flawed leader whose ideals shaped the nation even as his personal actions contradicted them.",
    page6: "Jefferson's words in the Declaration of Independence continue to serve as a foundation for American ideas about equality and rights, influencing later movements for abolition, women's suffrage, and civil rights. The Louisiana Purchase permanently changed the shape and future of the United States, opening vast lands for westward expansion. His vision for public education helped shape the development of American universities. His legacy remains debated today because of the gap between his ideals and his actions regarding slavery.",
    page7: "Thomas Jefferson wrote the Declaration of Independence in 1776 and later served as the third U.S. president, most notably completing the Louisiana Purchase in 1803, which doubled the nation's size. He commissioned the Lewis and Clark Expedition to explore and map the new western territory. Despite his writings on liberty and equality, he enslaved hundreds of people throughout his life, a contradiction historians still study closely. His ideas about rights and government remain central to American political thought today."
  }
