  "Patriotic Songs": {
    page1: "Patriotic songs are music written to express love for and pride in one's country, often performed during national holidays, sporting events, and official ceremonies. In the United States, well-known examples include \"The Star-Spangled Banner,\" the national anthem, along with \"America the Beautiful\" and \"My Country, 'Tis of Thee.\" These songs typically celebrate national history, values, and symbols like the flag. They help unite people through shared musical tradition and public performance.",
    page2: "Many American patriotic songs were written during moments of national significance, such as war or major historical anniversaries, when people felt a strong need to express unity and pride. \"The Star-Spangled Banner\" was written by Francis Scott Key in 1814 during the War of 1812, after he watched the American flag survive a night of British bombardment at Fort McHenry in Baltimore. \"America the Beautiful,\" written by Katharine Lee Bates in 1893, was inspired by the view from Pikes Peak in Colorado and celebrates the country's natural landscapes. These songs became popular through public performances, sheet music, and eventually radio and television broadcasts.",
    page3: "\"The Star-Spangled Banner\" officially became the national anthem of the United States in 1931, over a century after it was written. Its lyrics describe the flag still flying over Fort McHenry after a British attack, symbolizing American resilience. \"America the Beautiful\" praises the country's landscapes, from \"purple mountain majesties\" to \"amber waves of grain,\" and is sometimes suggested as an alternative anthem because its melody is easier to sing. \"My Country, 'Tis of Thee,\" written in 1831, uses the same melody as the British anthem \"God Save the King\" but with new American lyrics celebrating liberty.",
    page4: "Patriotic songs are typically performed at public events like sporting games, school assemblies, Fourth of July celebrations, and presidential inaugurations. Musicians and singers, sometimes famous performers, are often invited to perform the national anthem at major events to open ceremonies with a shared national moment. Students commonly learn these songs in school as part of music and social studies education. Over time, some patriotic songs have also been performed as protest or tribute, such as instrumental versions played during times of national mourning.",
    page5: "Francis Scott Key, a lawyer, wrote the lyrics to \"The Star-Spangled Banner\" as a poem after witnessing the battle firsthand from a ship in Baltimore's harbor, and it was later set to an existing tune. Composers and lyricists like Katharine Lee Bates used their own personal experiences and travels to shape the imagery found in patriotic songs. Performances of the national anthem have sometimes become moments of protest, such as athletes kneeling during the anthem to draw attention to social issues, showing that patriotic songs can hold different meanings for different people. These moments highlight ongoing conversations about patriotism, protest, and free expression in America.",
    page6: "Patriotic songs continue to play a central role in American public life, uniting people during celebrations and solemn occasions alike. \"The Star-Spangled Banner\" remains the official national anthem, performed at virtually every major national and sporting event. These songs are also used to teach history and civics, connecting students to key moments like the War of 1812. Discussions and debates about how and when these songs are performed remain part of ongoing conversations about patriotism and free speech.",
    page7: "Patriotic songs like \"The Star-Spangled Banner,\" written by Francis Scott Key in 1814, and \"America the Beautiful,\" written in 1893, express pride in American history, values, and landscapes. \"The Star-Spangled Banner\" became the official national anthem in 1931 and is performed at major public events. These songs are taught in schools and connect students to historical events like the War of 1812. They remain central to American civic and cultural life today."
  }
