  "Statue of Liberty": {
    page1: "The Statue of Liberty is a large copper statue standing on Liberty Island in New York Harbor, given to the United States by France as a gift celebrating friendship and shared ideals of liberty. Dedicated in 1886, it depicts a robed woman holding a torch in one hand and a tablet in the other, symbolizing freedom and law. For millions of immigrants arriving by ship in the late 1800s and early 1900s, the statue was often the first glimpse of America they saw. It remains one of the most recognized symbols of freedom and opportunity in the world.",
    page2: "The idea for the statue came from French historian Édouard de Laboulaye, who proposed the gift in the 1860s to celebrate the friendship between France and the United States, as well as America's success in abolishing slavery and building a democratic republic. French sculptor Frédéric Auguste Bartholdi designed the statue, drawing inspiration from Roman goddess imagery representing liberty. Funding for the statue came from the French public, while Americans raised money separately to build its pedestal, with newspaper publisher Joseph Pulitzer famously encouraging small donations from ordinary citizens. Construction took years, with the completed statue shipped from France to New York in pieces in 1885.",
    page3: "The Statue of Liberty stands 305 feet tall, including its pedestal, and was, at the time of its completion, one of the tallest structures in the world. Its official name is \"Liberty Enlightening the World,\" and it was dedicated on October 28, 1886. The statue's internal iron framework was engineered by Gustave Eiffel, who later built the Eiffel Tower in Paris. A poem called \"The New Colossus,\" written by Emma Lazarus, was later added to the statue's pedestal in 1903, including the famous line welcoming \"your tired, your poor, your huddled masses yearning to breathe free.\"",
    page4: "Ships carrying immigrants to the United States, especially through nearby Ellis Island starting in 1892, passed directly by the Statue of Liberty as they entered New York Harbor. For many immigrants, seeing the statue was an emotional moment symbolizing the start of a new life in America. The statue's torch represents enlightenment, while the tablet in her other hand bears the date July 4, 1776, marking American independence. Broken chains lie at her feet, symbolizing freedom from oppression and tyranny.",
    page5: "Frédéric Auguste Bartholdi spent years designing and refining the statue's appearance, reportedly using his own mother as inspiration for the statue's face. Everyday French citizens and Americans, including schoolchildren, contributed small donations to help fund the statue and its pedestal, showing broad public support for the project on both sides of the Atlantic. Millions of immigrants who passed the statue on their way to Ellis Island carried personal memories of that moment throughout their lives, often passing the story down to their descendants. The statue has since become deeply connected to America's identity as a nation shaped by immigration.",
    page6: "The Statue of Liberty remains one of the most visited monuments in the United States, drawing millions of tourists each year to Liberty Island. It continues to symbolize freedom, democracy, and the immigrant experience central to American history and identity. It has appeared in countless films, artworks, and works of literature as shorthand for American ideals. The statue was designated a National Monument in 1924 and remains under the care of the National Park Service.",
    page7: "The Statue of Liberty, a gift from France dedicated in 1886, stands in New York Harbor as a symbol of freedom and welcomed millions of immigrants arriving in the late 1800s and early 1900s. Designed by Frédéric Auguste Bartholdi and engineered by Gustave Eiffel, it stands 305 feet tall including its pedestal. Emma Lazarus's poem \"The New Colossus,\" added in 1903, gave the statue its famous welcoming words. It remains a defining symbol of American liberty and the immigrant experience today."
  }
