  "Liberty Bell": {
    page1: "The Liberty Bell is a large bronze bell in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, best known as a symbol of American independence and freedom, despite cracking and never being fully repaired. It was originally cast in 1752 for the Pennsylvania State House, now known as Independence Hall. The bell became famous for its use in celebrating important events, including, according to tradition, the reading of the Declaration of Independence. Today it stands as one of the most recognizable symbols of American liberty.",
    page2: "The bell was commissioned in 1751 to commemorate the fiftieth anniversary of Pennsylvania's original 1701 charter of laws, which included protections for religious freedom. It was cast in London and shipped to Philadelphia, but it cracked the first time it was rung after arrival in 1752, and local workers recast it using the original metal. Its inscription, taken from the Bible, reads \"Proclaim Liberty throughout all the Land unto all the Inhabitants thereof,\" giving it deep symbolic meaning even before the American Revolution. It hung in the State House steeple through the Revolutionary era, a period during which the building also housed the Continental Congress.",
    page3: "The bell weighs approximately 2,080 pounds and is inscribed with the biblical phrase about proclaiming liberty, along with the year it was cast, 1752. Its famous large crack developed sometime in the early to mid-1800s, likely from repeated ringing over many years, and attempts to repair it with a \"stop hole drilled\" crack ultimately failed. It was last rung in 1846 for George Washington's birthday, after which the crack worsened and made it unsafe to ring again. It hangs today in the Liberty Bell Center near Independence Hall in Philadelphia, both part of Independence National Historical Park.",
    page4: "The Liberty Bell rang on important occasions in early Philadelphia, including announcements of new laws and public gatherings, though historians note the popular story of it ringing to celebrate the signing of the Declaration of Independence in 1776 cannot be confirmed. It became widely associated with the abolitionist movement in the 1830s, when antislavery activists adopted it as a symbol and gave it the name \"Liberty Bell,\" since before that it was simply called the State House Bell. Its image and inscription were used on posters and materials calling for the end of slavery. This association helped transform it from a local artifact into a national symbol of freedom.",
    page5: "Abolitionists in the 19th century, including many who had never seen the actual bell, embraced its inscription about \"liberty throughout all the land\" as a powerful call to end slavery. Later, women's suffrage activists in the early 1900s also used replicas of the Liberty Bell, with clappers chained shut, to symbolize women's lack of voting rights until they were granted the right to vote. Civil rights activists in the 20th century likewise invoked the bell's symbolism in calling for equal rights for all Americans. These varied uses show how the bell's message of liberty has been reclaimed by different movements seeking to expand freedom.",
    page6: "The Liberty Bell remains a powerful symbol of American independence and the ongoing pursuit of liberty and equality for all citizens. It draws over a million visitors each year to Philadelphia, where it is displayed near Independence Hall. Its image appears on stamps, coins, and countless pieces of American memorabilia. Its cracked, imperfect form has, ironically, made it an even more meaningful symbol, representing a nation still working to fully live up to its ideals.",
    page7: "The Liberty Bell, cast in 1752 for Philadelphia's State House, became a symbol of American independence despite its famous crack, which developed over decades of ringing. Its inscription calling to \"proclaim liberty throughout all the land\" made it a rallying symbol for abolitionists in the 1830s and later for suffragists and civil rights activists. It last rang in 1846 and now sits on display near Independence Hall. It remains one of the most recognized symbols of American freedom."
  }
