  "Judicial Review": {
    page1: "Judicial review is the power of courts, especially the Supreme Court, to examine laws and government actions and determine whether they are constitutional. If a court finds a law or action violates the Constitution, it can strike it down, meaning it can no longer be enforced. This power, though not explicitly written into the original Constitution, was firmly established by the landmark Supreme Court case Marbury v. Madison in 1803. Judicial review remains one of the most important powers held by the judicial branch of American government.",
    page2: "When the Constitution was drafted in 1787, it created a judicial branch but did not explicitly state whether courts had the power to strike down laws passed by Congress or actions taken by the president. Early American leaders debated how much power courts should have relative to the elected legislative and executive branches. The issue came to a head in the case Marbury v. Madison, which arose from a political dispute during the transition between the Adams and Jefferson presidential administrations in 1801. Chief Justice John Marshall's ruling in this case in 1803 firmly established the principle of judicial review as a core power of the Supreme Court.",
    page3: "In Marbury v. Madison, decided in 1803, Chief Justice John Marshall ruled that a section of the Judiciary Act of 1789 was unconstitutional, marking the first time the Supreme Court struck down a federal law. Marshall's opinion argued that since the Constitution is the supreme law of the land, it is the judicial branch's duty to determine when laws conflict with it and to declare such laws invalid. This ruling established judicial review as an ongoing and essential power of the Supreme Court, even though the power was not explicitly written into the Constitution's text. Since 1803, judicial review has been used in many significant Supreme Court cases, shaping American law on issues ranging from civil rights to government power.",
    page4: "When a law or government action is challenged as unconstitutional, the case can work its way through the court system, potentially reaching the Supreme Court for a final decision. The Supreme Court examines the disputed law or action, comparing it against the text and principles of the Constitution to determine whether it is permissible. If the Court rules a law unconstitutional, that law can no longer be legally enforced, though Congress or state legislatures can sometimes pass new legislation addressing the same issue in a way that meets constitutional requirements. This process allows the judicial branch to serve as a check on the legislative and executive branches.",
    page5: "Chief Justice John Marshall, who served from 1801 to 1835, played an especially influential role in shaping the power and authority of the Supreme Court, with Marbury v. Madison standing as one of his most significant rulings. Later Supreme Court justices have used judicial review to decide many landmark cases, including Brown v. Board of Education in 1954, which struck down school segregation laws, showing how this power has been used to expand civil rights over time. Judicial review remains a subject of ongoing debate, since unelected judges hold significant power to overturn laws passed by elected officials. These debates reflect the ongoing tension between judicial authority and democratic decision-making in American government.",
    page6: "Judicial review gives the Supreme Court significant power to check the actions of Congress and the president, ensuring laws align with the Constitution. It has been used throughout American history to shape major issues, including civil rights, government power, and individual freedoms. The power remains a defining feature of the American judicial branch, distinguishing it from many other countries' court systems. Judicial review continues to shape American law and government today through ongoing Supreme Court rulings.",
    page7: "Judicial review, the power of courts to strike down unconstitutional laws, was firmly established by the Supreme Court case Marbury v. Madison in 1803, decided by Chief Justice John Marshall. Though not explicitly written into the Constitution, it became a core power of the judicial branch, allowing courts to check Congress and the president. It has since shaped major legal decisions, including landmark civil rights cases. Judicial review remains a foundational and sometimes debated power within the American system of government."
  }
