  "Gettysburg Address": {
    page1: "The Gettysburg Address was a short speech delivered by President Abraham Lincoln on November 19, 1863, at the dedication of a national cemetery for soldiers who died in the Battle of Gettysburg. Though only about two minutes long and roughly 272 words, it became one of the most famous speeches in American history. Lincoln used the speech to redefine the purpose of the Civil War, framing it as a struggle to preserve democracy and ensure human equality. It remains a powerful statement of American democratic ideals.",
    page2: "The Battle of Gettysburg, fought July 1-3, 1863, was one of the bloodiest and most significant battles of the Civil War, resulting in over 50,000 combined casualties and marking a major turning point in the Union's favor. Following the battle, officials began planning a national cemetery in Gettysburg to properly honor the thousands of soldiers who had died there. President Lincoln was invited to give \"a few appropriate remarks\" at the cemetery's dedication ceremony, though the featured speaker that day was actually renowned orator Edward Everett, who spoke for nearly two hours before Lincoln's brief remarks. Lincoln used this occasion to deliver a message that would reshape how Americans understood the purpose and meaning of the war.",
    page3: "Lincoln's speech, delivered on November 19, 1863, lasted only about two minutes and contained just ten sentences, yet it became one of the most quoted speeches in American history. It began with the now-famous line referencing the nation's founding \"four score and seven years ago,\" connecting the Civil War directly to the principles of the Declaration of Independence. Lincoln argued that the war was being fought to ensure that \"government of the people, by the people, for the people, shall not perish from the earth.\" Despite its brevity, and Lincoln's own doubts about whether it would be remembered, the speech has endured as one of the most significant statements of American democratic values.",
    page4: "Lincoln carefully crafted the speech to be brief and focused, a deliberate contrast to Edward Everett's much longer, more traditional oratory style earlier that day. The speech reframed the Civil War's purpose, moving beyond simply preserving the Union to emphasizing the broader principle of human equality found in the Declaration of Independence. Newspapers across the country reprinted the speech, and it gradually gained recognition as a masterful and historically significant piece of American oratory. Lincoln's ability to convey profound ideas in remarkably few words has made the speech a model of concise, powerful writing studied for generations.",
    page5: "Lincoln reportedly wrote drafts of the speech both before and possibly during his train journey to Gettysburg, carefully choosing words to convey deep meaning in a brief format. Edward Everett, the day's main speaker, later wrote to Lincoln acknowledging that Lincoln's brief remarks had captured the significance of the occasion more effectively than his own lengthy address. The speech's emphasis on equality connected directly to the ongoing debate over slavery and the war's evolving purpose following the Emancipation Proclamation earlier that year. These circumstances show how a brief, carefully crafted speech could carry immense historical and philosophical weight.",
    page6: "The Gettysburg Address remains one of the most quoted and studied speeches in American history, encapsulating core democratic values in remarkably few words. It helped redefine the purpose of the Civil War as a struggle not just to preserve the Union but to ensure human equality and democratic government. Its words are inscribed at the Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., and remain widely taught in American schools. The speech continues to be cited as a defining statement of American democratic ideals.",
    page7: "The Gettysburg Address, delivered by Lincoln on November 19, 1863, at the dedication of a national cemetery, redefined the Civil War's purpose as a struggle to preserve \"government of the people, by the people, for the people.\" Though only about two minutes long, it became one of the most significant speeches in American history. It connected the war directly to the Declaration of Independence's principles of equality. The speech remains a powerful and enduring statement of American democratic ideals."
  }
