  "Amelia Earhart": {
    page1: "Amelia Earhart was an American aviator best known for being the first woman to fly solo across the Atlantic Ocean in 1932. Born in 1897 in Kansas, she became one of the most famous and celebrated pilots of her era, setting numerous aviation records and advocating for women's opportunities in aviation. She disappeared in 1937 while attempting to fly around the world, and her fate remains one of aviation history's most enduring mysteries. Earhart remains an iconic figure representing courage, adventure, and the expansion of opportunities for women.",
    page2: "Earhart developed an early interest in adventurous, unconventional activities as a young woman, eventually becoming fascinated with flying after attending an air show in 1920. She took her first flying lesson in 1921 and quickly became dedicated to aviation, purchasing her own plane and working various jobs to fund her growing passion for flying. In 1928, Earhart gained national attention as the first woman to fly across the Atlantic Ocean, though she flew as a passenger rather than a pilot on that flight. This experience motivated her to pursue solo flying achievements to prove women could accomplish the same feats as male aviators.",
    page3: "In May 1932, Earhart became the first woman to fly solo across the Atlantic Ocean, completing the roughly 2,000-mile flight from Newfoundland, Canada, to Ireland in just under 15 hours. This achievement made her one of the most celebrated aviators in the world, earning her numerous awards, including the Distinguished Flying Cross from the U.S. Congress. She went on to set additional records, including being the first person to fly solo across the Pacific Ocean from Hawaii to California in 1935. In 1937, Earhart attempted to become the first woman to fly around the world, but her plane disappeared over the Pacific Ocean on July 2, 1937, near Howland Island, and neither she nor her navigator, Fred Noonan, were ever found.",
    page4: "Earhart's Atlantic solo flight in 1932 required careful planning, significant piloting skill, and considerable personal risk, given the limitations of early aviation technology and navigation methods. Her attempted around-the-world flight in 1937 was an ambitious roughly 29,000-mile journey, and she had already completed most of the route before disappearing during the flight's most dangerous and remote Pacific segment. Despite an extensive search effort by the U.S. Navy and Coast Guard following her disappearance, no definitive wreckage or remains were ever conclusively found. Various theories about her fate have been proposed over the decades, though none have been definitively proven.",
    page5: "Amelia Earhart was known for her determination, courage, and advocacy for expanding opportunities for women in aviation and other fields, using her fame to encourage other women to pursue careers typically dominated by men. She helped found the Ninety-Nines, an organization supporting female pilots, and served as a career counselor at Purdue University, encouraging women's ambitions in various fields. Her disappearance in 1937 deeply affected the public and generated enormous, sustained interest in solving the mystery of her fate, an interest that continues among researchers and historians today. Her legacy combines both her genuine aviation achievements and the enduring intrigue surrounding her final flight.",
    page6: "Amelia Earhart's aviation achievements helped demonstrate women's capability in fields previously dominated by men, inspiring generations of women to pursue careers in aviation and beyond. Her disappearance remains one of the most famous unsolved mysteries in aviation history, continuing to generate research, expeditions, and public fascination decades later. She remains a powerful symbol of adventure, determination, and breaking barriers for women in traditionally male-dominated fields. Earhart's legacy continues to inspire interest in aviation history and women's achievements today.",
    page7: "Amelia Earhart, born in 1897, became the first woman to fly solo across the Atlantic Ocean in 1932, going on to set numerous other aviation records and advocate for women in flying. In 1937, she disappeared over the Pacific Ocean while attempting to fly around the world, a mystery that remains unsolved today. Her achievements helped demonstrate women's capabilities in aviation and inspired generations of female pilots. Earhart remains an iconic symbol of courage, adventure, and expanding opportunities for women."
  }
